The first virtual provider is already coming to Czechia this year.
Maybe
The mobile radio market in the Czech Republic is fairly mature, the Czech suppliers offer virtually all services, as they are offered by their partners in Western Europe.
Nevertheless, something is missing here - a virtual provider that forces the classic to lower prices.
Perhaps this will not be waited any longer.
The fact that Czech mobile providers work at all in Europe, we have often reported on Mobile.cz.
However, this also confirmed the ČTU telecommunications authority, which pointed out that the price for an SMS here is higher than the rest of the European Union.
Following the last steps of the European Commission in the area of roaming charges, it is likely that there will be a paradoxical situation - for some Czech mobile customers, SMS will be cheaper than at home.
How is it that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really makes a fight.
Perhaps it sounds paradox, but in the Czech Republic there are three mobile networks and a penetration of over 100 %.
On the other hand, mobile providers are happy to agree that there is very much competition on the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTU) Pavel Dvořák, who had in the past often said that there was no room for another provider in the Czech Republic.
It is likely that a classic provider with its own network will no longer have many chances (by the way, he would probably not find any more frequencies).
But there is another possibility - a virtual provider.
It was precisely the entry of virtual providers into the mobile radio market that led to a significant price reduction, which the classic mobile providers also had to respond to.
Before the entry of such companies as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile there were similar voices on the UK market as in the Czech Republic.
However, it has shown that there is room for such providers and that they can really be successful.
By the way, you do not need to look for examples for a long time.
In February this we reported on the start of the virtual provider Mobilking in Poland.
In just half a year, this provider managed to win more than 100 thousand customers and thus rise to the country's fifth largest provider.
Behind Mobilking is the Penta Financial Group, which has U:phone in Czechia.
The advantage of virtual providers is that one can focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to function effectively, virtual providers need much less customers than a classic provider.
They do not need a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual providers are usually profiled as low-cost companies - they offer cheap telephone calls and SMS, which is often accompanied by a less extensive service supply.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers at least half cheaper SMS than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a pretty good chess game to put on a non-climbing target group.
This provider is specifically addressed to men.
"Choose real guys Mobilking - the provider they like and can trust," said David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, the operator company of this virtual provider.
It is hard to say whether a similar concept could be found in the Czech Republic as well as in Poland.
The press spokesman for Vodafone Miroslav Čepícý also doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a market segment on which most virtual providers are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the provision of services."
In Czech Republic, no chance, mobile providers mean
However, it is almost certain that if a virtual mobile provider conquers the Czech Republic, this will not be mobile.
"We are talking about an expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not seem hopeful.
It will rather come to a market entry from Mobilking in other countries of our region," says Jana Studničková, press spokesman for the Penta Financial Group.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the current mobile providers in the Czech Republic are not pleased with this idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything they can to ensure that there is no potential competitor.
Your interest in starting a virtual mobile phone provider has been showing the GTS Novera group for a long time that wants to take another step to become a real competitor of Telefónica O2 in the field of company customers.
"We have a great interest in providing not only fixed-net, but also mobile telecommunications services to our customers.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile providers.
With some of them, we were already able to make progress in the negotiations," said the press spokesman of the Pavel Kaidl Group.
Maybe better times are coming now.
Unofficial information indicates that the first virtual provider may be expected by the end of the year.
But so far this is surrounded by an insurmountable wall of silence.
"At this point, we do not assume that there is room in the Czech Republic for a fully-fledged virtual provider.
The Czech market is very specific to other markets.
To date, we have not been addressed by a complex and serious project in this area," he said in his statement for Mobil.cz Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefónica O2.
Other suppliers also point to the specific nature of the Czech market.
The press spokesman for T-Mobile Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the statement of O2: "So far we have not found a viable and mutually beneficial project to build on."
And she adds: "The network of T-Mobile will hardly show up a virtual provider until the end of the year.
At this point, we should have already presented a concrete offer to think so in the short term."
Vodafone focuses more on meeting the requirements of its own 3G licence.
Miroslav Čepíký means: "For negotiations with potential virtual providers, we are open, especially in the area of cost sharing and infrastructure.
This is exactly what we considered from the customer's point of view as the best.
The main strategy of Vodafone in this area is to look for a partner to build a shared network for a fast mobile internet."
The responsible authorities - with the suppliers hand in hand
The behaviour of mobile providers is easy to understand, another provider called more competition, which would lead to lower prices and thus also to a decrease in profits.
Why, then, should such a competitor be made easier to enter the market?
The fact that suppliers can pull on a string when it comes to something is also evidence of the long track and here about the origin of U:phone.
Perhaps the strongest pressure towards ČTU came from the company T-Mobile when U:phon came to the market.
This is also evidenced by the publicly available information from the ČTU website.
But right now U:phone is suitable as an argument why a virtual provider should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrová noted: "The competitive environment of the mobile radio market has recently also been strengthened by the market entry of a fourth mobile provider.
In view of the nature of the mobile radio market in the Czech Republic, it is obvious that a new operator would make high demands on the market itself and in particular its services."
In view of this approach by mobile providers, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is surprising.
This is not just the attitude of the ČTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike Britain and other highly developed countries - does not have the competence to engage in economic competition.
It is exclusively owned by the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (UOHS).
This, however, referred to this whole problem of his very typical attitude.
"The market entry of a virtual mobile provider would then be possible after a contract has been concluded between a mobile provider and a virtual provider over the admission of the necessary infrastructure.
So far, no such contract has been concluded, because the offer of potential stakeholders was probably not sufficiently interesting for the classic providers," Kristian Chalupa, in his response to our request from the Department of External Relations of the ÚOHS.
Such a formulation would not surprise the representatives of the supplier.
This is more than worrying from an authority that represents consumer interests and should, among other things, ensure that no one abuses its position on the market.
In particular, when Kristian Chalupa adds: "In abroad, where virtual providers work quite normally, it is to be observed that their market entry has contributed to a price reduction in mobile telephone services."
However, it is likely that the pressure on the proper functioning of the market and a price decline does not fall within the interests of the ÚOHS.
In this case, it is truly shocking that the almost already touching consistency of the three mobile providers resulting from their reactions.
The question of whether this really is just an accident is on hand.
Just as the absolute same gas price at the fuel stations is certainly only a coincidence and the result of a hard competition.
"The Authority has not discovered in this case any signs that would imply action directed against competition, and thus it has no reason to intervene in any way on the matter.
None of the suppliers have a dominant market position, so they also do not have the corresponding increased responsibility for their operations on the market.
The necessary instruments for opening up the mobile radio market for virtual providers are probably also missing from the telecommunications regulatory authority," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets, drawn up by the ČTU, according to telecommunications from the point of view of economic competition is a single market.
On such a market, of course, none of the Czech mobile providers have a dominant position.
Some legal experts, however, offer a different view - the consent of the network operator is always required for the market entry of a virtual provider.
And the mobile provider - logically - has the monopoly for his network.
This means that in a particular segment he is necessarily taking a dominant position.
However, even if one does not agree with this argument, it should be at least a warning for the ÚOHS that three mobile providers are acting in a similar manner.
A number of interested parties (including the mentioned company GTS Novera) argue that they are faced with very similar obstacles in negotiations with all suppliers.
The discharge of responsibility to the ČTU is then a rather common trick in the telecommunications services, with which the ÚOHS distanced itself from the whole matter.
This has already been observed in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, the Novelle of the Telecommunications Act recently adopted failed to implement the extension of ČTU's competence in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, even though a number of experts had promised to improve the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this very well, but they probably have different interests.
It's okay if no one looks.
Only once remains the operation of any pseudo-virtual provider, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
There are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telecommunications services, but are only partially public.
This is usually the case for companies operating in the area of multi-level marketing.
For example, Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and others offer their own mobile phone services.
The price lists of these companies are usually only selected.
The joke is that the company acts as a classic company customer, which orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer he then receives special price offers (and other offers).
The problem is that the business conditions of all Czech mobile providers prohibit a similar type of resale.
"If there are cases that you describe, then it can be an infringement of the contractual conditions with which we will then deal, which can lead to an end of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
However, it is quite unlikely that such a thing will not happen to mobile providers.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned, thousands of customers may be involved.
However, no operator opposes such an action.
These companies do not allow them to make unnecessary profits, while, unlike the actual virtual suppliers, they are not affected by the actual official marketing.
Miroslav Čepíký points out possible problems: "The law enables such kinds of speculation, although the services of these companies are used only by a very small percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card does not run on their phone, so they cannot fully have it as normal customers of mobile providers."
But this alone had to be at least unusual for the ČTU.
There is also a further question for the ÚOHS.
Do mobile providers close their eyes before such a move, why do they block themselves from a virtual provider?
It is to be added that the ÚOHS has quite strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it does not have to satisfy itself with the provider's statement, they did not know anything about it and their business conditions would prohibit this.
When Czech Republic is no longer the most expensive
As has already been pointed out in the text, the market entry of virtual providers brought a significant price decline in the various services.
In practically all countries where virtual providers were created, classic providers have tried to prevent their origins from practically more or less.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - a too small, or too saturated market, problems in the quality of services, etc.
In the highly developed countries, however, it is precisely in these moments that regulatory bodies intervene, not in any way the interests of mobile providers, but those who tried to prove to their customers.
Whether through formal measures or non-formal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and that they followed further.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory bodies are throwing themselves into the whole case like a hot potato.
Based on our experience, we cannot escape the impression that uncertainty in the competences in these cases is more than favourable.
But we don't throw the flint into the grain.
If the background information is correct and a virtual provider will soon appear, the Czech mobile phone market may be moving again soon.
If a provider permits the creation of a virtual mobile provider, the ÚOHS will not remain inactive if it is to refuse (to discriminate) other stakeholders.
And then the Czechs will finally stop calling more expensive than the rest of Europe.
