The psychology of excess - or why we are willing to pay more
In the case of auctions, the buyers tend to spend more and thus overestimate the error bid.
Neurologists and economic researchers at the University of New York have now succeeded in discovering the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to a study published in the "Science" magazine, people don't want to give in to a competition, such as an auction on eBay, and are therefore willing to pay even higher prices.
The researchers have tried to explore the neurological scheme of this "game" with experimental auctions.
A group of volunteers should play Lotto, while the others participate in a playful action - in both cases the active brain regions of the subjects were studied by functional magnetic resonance (fMRI).
In both games, the participants were able to earn money, however, an increased activity of the Straitum, a complex below the brain, was measured at the loss of the auction, in which the opponent's overcoming played an essential role.
In addition to many other functions, this brain region is responsible for the "self-reward" of the nervous system.
The researchers therefore felt that the price increase could be explained by avoiding an over-reaction of the Straitum.
In order to undermine their thesis, the economists in the research group have hired additional research to track the money.
In this case, three groups against a partner should cooperate under different conditions.
The control group was informed of the true value of the product and then they made their efforts.
In addition to this, another group was promised $15 reward, in case they came out as winners of the game.
The third group received 15 dollars before the auction, which were also lost in the case of a lost game.
Thus, the difference between the two groups was only that the emphasis was on the one on the gain, while on the other on the loss.
However, as evidence of the assumptions expressed by neurologists, the members of the "against losing" group were willing to make higher efforts than those in the control group or the "gain" group.
"These results cannot be attributed to any previous economic theory.
These have so far justified the behaviours observed in auctions only with the joy of winning, or the avoidance of risk.
The contradiction between these two theories has been resolved through the illustrative neurological procedures, so we have now prepared a third statement" - said Andrew Schotter, professor of the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When is the doctor to ask?
Around half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed under the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people is estimated to be hundreds of thousands, but only seven thousand are treated, which means that patients often do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the collective term for various virus-induced infectious liver diseases.
Symptoms are often similar - liver inflammation and jaundice are common, but the causes and diseases differ.
Depending on the origins, the hepatitis virus is spread to two different species: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. through contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C and D can be transmitted to the virus through blood and other body fluids (e.g. sperm, thyroid secretion or storage).
Travellers are recommended for an vaccine against the viruses A and B, however, there is no vaccine against the virus C.
The symptoms of hepatitis A occur approximately two or three weeks after the consumption of the contaminated food and are generally accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal pain and vomiting.
Then the yellow look appears on the skin and in the eyes, the chair is bright, the urine is dark, and healing can take up to two or three weeks.
Worldwide, about 1 million people die each year from hepatitis B-related, far more serious diseases such as liver cancer and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason for this is that according to estimates, only every 10 infected people are treated with medicinal products.
Hepatitis C may also have serious consequences: untreated it may lead to liver cirrhosis and liver cancer.
Most infected people do not even know about their disease, as the trigger destroys the liver cells at home - in many cases the first symptoms occur after 20-30 years.
Therefore, timely prevention, such as regular control tests, is essential.
There are three groups in which this disease is more common: those who underwent a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts, and tattoos.
Currently, the number of chronic hepatitis C patients worldwide is estimated at 200 million.
Since the disease is already detectable in a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to seek the home doctor for the first signs of unknown origin.
In due course, the disease can be cured, the virus can be eradicated, thus banning the risk of infection and preventing cancer.
The 30th September is the World Day of Hepatitis, 2004 for the first time of patient representations worldwide.
The aim of the action is to strengthen awareness of this chronic liver inflammation caused by viruses, their origin and the importance of early detection.
