Scientists at Oxford University have carried out an interesting experiment: It was examined how far the belief in God affects the human feeling of pain, the British magazine "Telegraph" reported.
During the rather bizarre investigation, 12 believers and atheists received electroshocks while studying a painting of the mother of God.
As the results showed, the believers could turn off most of the pain.
By means of a brain scan technology, it was even proven that Catholics could activate part of their brain, which is responsible for pain control.
The study was the first in a research project involving philosophers and theologians from different departments of the University.
In the trial, the samplers were connected to the left hand, which gave the electroshocks.
The participants were asked to concentrate heavily on two paintings: to one image of the mother of God, painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century, and to the other Leonardo da Vinci "The Lady with Hermelin".
The researchers hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary among the believers would raise a sort of religious trance, while they chose the image of da Vinci, because it was hardly different from the other painting and was perceived as comforting.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and received a total of 20 electroshocks in four stages at that time, while they should see either the religious or the other painting.
The Catholics reported that they had felt "in security" at the sight of God's mother, as if they were "careful", and they had felt "peace and peace".
While considering the religious painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of their eyes.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also took part in the attempt, thought that similar effects could also be caused by other, powerful images also among the atheists, but only the corresponding photo had to be found.
"We should find a picture that triggers very positive feelings, such as a mother or a father," says the psychologist.
The Anglican Bishop Tom Wright welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change our personality, and it does in many cases," Wright said.
According to these excellent results, only the question remains as to what effect a Madonna image of Leonardo or another comparable painter would have on the pain regulation of the believers.
Would the high-quality virgin Mary achieve even better results?
