What would be the best method for developing new technologies for accident prevention if not imitating the obstacle sensors from nature?
For example, the bees.
The CEATEC in Japan presented an amazing project in which the Nissan engineers of Hummeln were inspired by the creation of new accident prevention systems.
In cooperation with Tokyo University, Nissan has built the BR23C-controlled biomimetic system, a mini car, equipped with the characteristics of the bees, with the aim of supporting the development of a system that avoids any collisions.
In the flight, each bee forms its own, oval "private area", which is very similar to our own "protection shield", said Kazuhiro Doi, product manager for technology PR and research development, at the exhibition.
The compounded eye of the bee, which can be seen in each direction and at an angle of over 300 degrees, plays an important role in this.
In order to imitate the function of the compounded eye, the researchers intervene on the idea of laser-controlled distance meter.
This identifies obstacles to the BR23C in a 180-degree field of view within 2 meters, calculates its distances and sends signals to the microprocessor on board, which immediately initiates the collision-avoiding process.
The obstacle is recorded in second break parts, and the author immediately changes the course, similar to the movement of the bees by turning the tires around the corresponding angle.
Unlike previous systems, this maneuver takes place instinctively.
"If it wasn't so, the autobot couldn't react quickly enough to avoid the obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the "Mobility Laboratory" and the autobot project.
The system must react instinctively and immediately, since this technology corresponds to the inner and most vulnerable part of the shield - a layer, within the accidents, is still considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect the behavior of the bees when they avoid other bees.
And this must go on for a second.
However, the deviation, unlike the bees, can not be up, down, or even diagonally - it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction of the elasticity of the tires.
While the bees here are endlessly open to avoid other bees, the researchers were able to use only the movement of rotation, or acceleration and brake.
The BR23C contains lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and more energy efficient and therefore have a longer life than conventional lithium ion batteries.
Andoh explained that it comes to the instinctive, intelligent reaction, and less to the processing of the data, and even less to the ability to store it.
This device only needs to process and react to some inputs per second.
It does not need to store it, or produce an intuitive, logical reaction based on previous maneuvers, so that it is currently only using a handful KB memory.
There's no need for gigabytes and megabytes of heavy memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which will be in production series within the next ten years, according to Nissan's estimate.
Another application could be found in GPS satellite navigation by deliberately driving the driver around obstacles and thus leading him to his goal.
